ODE IV.

This ode is an expression of friendship to seminam, a Roman knight of high standing. He was a poet and a soldier. He had been a school-fellow, a long-tried and intimate friend of Horace, who here tells him, that, as they had passed the best of their days together in toils and dangers, he now wishes to retire with him, and to spond the evening of life in tranquillity, either at his own seat at Tibur, or with Septimius at Tarentum.

ODE V.

There has been some doubt who the Pompey here addressed was; some suppose it to have been Pompeius Varus. But it is pretty generally believed that the address is to Pompeius Grosphus, He was an early friend and companion of our poet, and was with him at the battle of Philippi. He also continued in opposition to Au- gustus afterwards. But when the peace was concluded between Sextus Pompey and the Triumvirate, a general amnesty was grant- ed to all Pompey's party.
